SIMPLE: punctual
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Punctual
<hw>Punc"tu*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>ponctuel</ets> (cf. Sp. <ets>puntual</ets>, It.
<ets>puntuale</ets>), from L. <ets>punctum</ets> point. See
<er>Point</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting in a point; limited
to a point; unextended.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧This
<xex>punctual</xex> spot.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The theory of the <qex>punctual</qex> existence of the soul.</q>
<rj><qau> Krauth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Observant of nice points; punctilious;
precise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Punctual</qex> to tediousness in all that he relates.</q>
<rj><qau> Bp. Burnet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So much on <qex>punctual</qex> niceties they stand.</q>
<rj><qau>C. Pitt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Appearing or done at, or adhering exactly to, a
regular or an appointed time; precise; prompt; <as>as, a
<ex>punctual</ex> man; a <ex>punctual</ex> payment</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The race of the undeviating and <xex>punctual</xex> sun.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These sharp strokes [of a pendulum], with their inexorably steady
intersections, so agree with our successive thoughts that they seem like
the <qex>punctual</qex> stops counting off our very souls into the
past.</q> <rj><qau> J. Martineau.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1163 --></p>

<p><ent>Punctualist</ent>⟦br⟧
